cknowledgments and Introduction available free, subscription required for full text-->, Boulder, CO: Westview Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8133-3693-0}}\n*{{cite journal | doi=10.2307/481499 | last1=Goldfrank |first1= Esther Schiff |year=1983 |title=Another View. Margaret and Me |journal = Ethnohistory |volume= 30 |issue=1 |pages= 1\u201314 |jstor=481499}}\n*Holmes, Lowell D. (1987). ''Quest for the Real Samoa: the Mead/Freeman Controversy and Beyond''. South Hadley, MA: Bergin and Garvey.\n*[[Jane Howard (journalist)|Howard, Jane]]. (1984). ''Margaret Mead: A Life'', New York: Simon and Schuster.\n*Keeley, Lawrence (1996). ''War Before Civilization: the Myth of the Peaceful Savage'' (Oxford University Press). {{ISBN|978-0-19-511912-1}}\n*Lapsley, Hilary. (1999). ''Margaret Mead and Ruth Benedict: The Kinship of Women''. [[University of Massachusetts Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-55849-181-6}}\n*{{cite journal | author = Leacock, Eleanor | year = 1988 | title = Anthropologists in Search of a Culture: Margaret Mead, Derek Freeman and All the Rest of Us | url = | journal = Central Issues in Anthropology | volume = 8 | issue = 1| pages = 3\u201320 | doi = 10.1525/cia.1988.8.1.3 }}\n*{{cite journal | author = Levy, Robert | year = 1984 | title = Mead, Freeman, and Samoa: The Problem of Seeing Things as They Are | url = | journal = Ethos | volume = 12 | issue = | pages = 85\u201392 | doi = 10.1525/eth.1984.12.1.02a00060 }}\n*Lutkehaus, Nancy C. (2008). ''Margaret Mead: The Making of an American Icon''. Princeton: Princeton University Press.  {{ISBN|978-0-691-00941-4}}\n*{{cite journal | author = Mageo, Jeannette | year = 1988 | title = ''Malosi'': A Psychological Exploration of Mead's and Freeman's Work and of Samoan Aggression | url = http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u?/PacificStudies,860 | journal = Pacific Studies | volume = 11 | issue = 2| pages = 25\u201365 }}\n* Mandler, Peter (2013). ''Return from the Natives: How Margaret Mead Won the Second World War and Lost the Cold War.'' New Haven, CT: Yale University Press.\n*{{cite journal | author = Marshall, Mac. | year = 1993 | title = The Wizard from Oz Meets the Wicked Witch of the East: Freeman, Mead, and Ethnographic Authority | url = | journal = American Ethnologist | volume = 20 | issue = 3| pages = 604\u2013617 | doi = 10.1525/ae.1993.20.3.02a00080 }}\n{{anchor|CITEREFMead1972}}\n*{{cite book |author=Mead, Margaret |title=Blackberry Winter: My Earlier Years |publisher=William Morrow |location=New York |year=1972 |pages= |isbn=978-0-688-00051-6 |doi= |accessdate= |url=https://archive.org/details/blackberrywinter00meadrich }}\n*Mead, Margaret. 1977. [https://web.archive.org/web/20170110161019/http://www.thegreatlecturelibrary.com/index.php?select=speaker&data=988 The Future as Frame for the Present]. Audio recording of a lecture delivered July 11, 1977.\n*{{cite journal | author = Metraux, Rhoda | year = 1980 | title = Margaret Mead. A Biographical Sketch | jstor =675870 | journal = American Anthropologist | volume = 82 | issue =2 | pages = 262\u2013269 | doi = 10.1525/aa.1980.82.2.02a00010 }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.2307/3177870 | author = Nardi, Bonnie |authorlink = Bonnie Nardi | last2 = Mead | year = 1984 | first2 = Margaret | last3 = Freeman | first3 = Derek | title = The Height of Her Powers: Margaret Mead's Samoa | jstor = 3177870| journal =Feminist Studies | volume = 10 | issue = 2| pages = 323\u2013337 }}\n*{{cite book | title=Visions of Culture: An Introduction to Anthropological Theories and Theorists | author=Moore, Jerry D. | year=2004 | publisher=Rowman Altamira | page=105 | isbn=978-0-7591-0411-2}}\n*{{cite journal |author1=Patience, Allan |author2=Josephy Smith | year = 1987 | title = Derek Freeman in Samoa: The Making and Unmaking of a Biobehavioral Myth | url = | journal = American Anthropologist | volume = 88 | issue = | pages = 157\u2013162 | doi = 10.1525/aa.1986.88.1.02a00160 }}\n*{{cite journal | author = Paxman, David B. | year = 1988 | title = Freeman, Mead, and the Eighteenth-Century Controversy over Polynesian Society | url =http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/u?/PacificStudies,879 | journal = Pacific Studies | volume = 11 | issue = 3| pages = 1\u201319 }}\n*Pinker, Steven A. (1997). ''How the Mind Works''. {{ISBN|978-0-393-04535-2}}\n*Sandall, Roger. (2001) ''The Culture Cult: Designer Tribalism and Other Essays''. {{ISBN|978-0-8133-3863-7}}\n*{{cite journal | author = Scheper-Hughes, Nancy | year = 1984 | title = The Margaret Mead Controversy: Culture, Biology, and Anthropological Inquiry | url = http://sfaa.metapress.com/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=0018-7259&volume=43&issue=1&spage=85 | journal = Human Organization | volume = 43 | issue = 1 | pages = 85\u201393 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130128220137/http://sfaa.metapress.com/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=0018-7259&volume=43&issue=1&spage=85 | archivedate = January 28, 2013 | doi = 10.17730/humo.43.1.362253166r6173m4 }}\n*{{cite journal | author = Shankman, Paul | year = 1996 | title = The History of Samoan Sexual Conduct and the Mead-Freeman Controversy | url = | journal = American Anthropologist | volume = 98 | issue = 3| pages = 555\u2013567 | doi = 10.1525/aa.1996.98.3.02a00090 }}\n*{{cite book | title=The Trashing of Margaret Mead: Anatomy of an Anthropological Controversy| author=Shankman, Paul | year=2009 | publisher=University of Wisconsin Press | isbn=978-0-299-23454-6}}\n*Shore, Brad. (1982) ''Sala'ilua: A Samoan Mystery''. New York: Columbia University Press.\n*{{cite journal | author = Stassinos, Elizabeth | year = 1998 | title = Response to Visweswaren, 'Race and the culture of anthropology' | url = | journal = American Anthropologist | volume = 100 | issue = 4| pages = 981\u2013983 | doi = 10.1525/aa.1998.100.4.981 }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1353/haa.0.0063 | first=Elizabeth |last=Stassinos | title=An Early Case of Personality: Ruth Benedict's Autobiographical Fragment and the Case of the Biblical \"Boaz\" | journal=Histories of Anthropology Annual | volume=5 | year=2009| pages=28\u201351 |issn=1557-637X }}\n*Virginia, Mary E. (2003). Benedict, Ruth (1887\u20131948). ''DISCovering U.S. History'' online edition, Detroit: Gale.\n*{{cite journal |author1=Young, R.E. |author2=S. Juan. | year = 1985 | title = Freeman's Margaret Mead Myth: The Ideological Virginity of Anthropologists | url = | journal = Australian and New Zealand Journal of Sociology | volume = 21 | issue =1 | pages = 64\u201381 | doi = 10.1177/144078338502100104 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisourceauthor}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* Online video: {{YouTube|GOCYhmnx6o8|Margaret Mead and Samoa}}.  Documentary about the [[Mead-Freeman controversy#The Mead-Freeman controversy|Mead-Freeman controversy]], including an interview with one of Mead's original informants.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070621113405/http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/audiofiles.html#mead Creative Intelligence: Female - \"The Silent Revolution: Creative Man In Contemporary Society\"] Talk at UC Berkeley, 1962 (online audio file)\n*[http://www.interculturalstudies.org The Institute for Intercultural Studies] \u2013 ethnographic institute founded by Mead, with resources relating to Mead's work\n**[http://www.interculturalstudies.org/Mead/biography.html Margaret Mead biography at IIS] not available. Visited on May 15, 2014.\n*[https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/mead/ Library of Congress, Margaret Mead: Human Nature and the Power of Culture]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061107221604/http://www.amnh.org/programs/mead/mead2006/index.php American Museum of Natural History, Margaret Mead Film & Video Festival]\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n78-93416}}\n*[http://www.voanews.com/specialenglish/2010-01-17-voa1.cfm \"Margaret Mead, 1901\u20131978: A Public Face of Anthropology\"]: brief biography, [[Voice of America]] Page doesn't exist. Visited on May 15, 2014.\n*[http://www.nasonline.org/publications/biographical-memoirs/memoir-pdfs/mead-margaret.pdf National Academy of Sciences Biographical Memoir]\n*[https://www.loc.gov/rr/rarebook/coll/059.html The Dell Paperback Collection] at the [[Library of Congress]] has first edition paperbacks of Mead's works.\n\n{{American Anthropological Association presidents}}\n{{systems}}\n{{Society for General Systems Research Presidents}}\n{{National Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mead, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:American anthropologists]]\n[[Category:American anthropology writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT anthropologists]]\n[[Category:American women anthropologists]]\n[[Category:American curators]]\n[[Category:American systems scientists]]\n[[Category:Psychological anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Visual anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Women systems scientists]]\n[[Category:Women science writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:DePauw University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kalinga Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:People associated with the American Museum of Natural History]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Anthropological Association]]\n[[Category:University of Rhode Island faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Youth empowerment people]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Anglicans]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Social Science Research Council]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT academics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Society of Woman Geographers]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed # to No.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Mead"}
{"title_page": "Neri Oxman", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Neri Oxman\n| birth_name         = \u05e0\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d5\u05e7\u05e1\u05de\u05df\u200e\n| native_name_lang   = he\n| image              = Neri Oxman by Noah Kalina.jpg\n| caption            = Oxman in 2017\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|02|06}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Design and the elastic mind|last=Antonelli|first=Paula|date=2008-01-01|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|isbn=9780870707322|location=NY, NY|pages=75|oclc=780473124}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Haifa]], Israel\n| nationality        = Israeli, American\n| alma_mater         = The [[Hebrew Reali School]] in Haifa, Israel <br /> [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]] (BA)<br />[[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]<br />[[Architectural Association School of Architecture|Architectural Association]] (MA)<br />[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (PhD)\n| occupation         = Associate professor of media arts and science<ref>{{cite web |url= http://singularityhub.com/2012/06/04/3d-printing-is-the-future-of-manufacturing-and-neri-oxman-shows-how-beautiful-it-can-be/ |title=3D Printing Is The Future Of Manufacturing And Neri Oxman Shows How Beautiful It Can Be|first= David J.|last= Hill|work=singularityhub.com |date= June 4, 2012|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>\n| notable_works      = ''Silk Pavilion'' (2013) <br /> ''Wanderers'' (2015) <br /> ''Material Ecology'' (2020)\n| awards             = [[Vilcek Prize]], 2014<br /> [[Earth Award for Future Crucial Design|Earth Award]], 2009\n| spouse             = [[Osvaldo Golijov]] (divorced)<br />[[Bill Ackman]] (2019\u2013present)<ref name=\"Mallozzi\">{{cite web |title=As If by Design, Their Connection Was Inevitable|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/19/fashion/weddings/as-if-by-design-their-connection-was-inevitable.html |last=Mallozzi|first=Vincent|date=January 19, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n| children           = 1 daughter\n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n   | allegiance      = {{flag|Israel}}\n   | branch          = [[File:Air Force Ensign of Israel.svg|21px]] [[Israeli Air Force]]\n   | serviceyears    = 1996-1999\n   | rank            = [[File:IAF segen.svg|16px]] [[First lieutenant]]\n}}\n}}\n<!-- end of infobox person -->\n\n'''Neri Oxman''' ({{lang-he|\u05e0\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d5\u05e7\u05e1\u05de\u05df}}; born 6 February 1976) is an [[American\u2013Israeli]] designer and professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] [[MIT Media Lab|Media Lab]], where she leads the Mediated Matter research group. She is known for art and architecture that combine design, biology, computing, and materials engineering.\n\nHer work embodies [[environmental design]] and [[digital morphogenesis]], with shapes and properties that are determined by their context.  She coined the phrase \"material ecology\" to define her work, placing materials in context.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.materialecology.com/|title=Material Ecology website|date=|publisher=|accessdate=October 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dirt.asla.org/2009/08/20/material-ecology/|title=Material Ecology|date=August 20, 2009|publisher=The Dirt|accessdate=April 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718021252/http://dirt.asla.org/2009/08/20/material-ecology/|archive-date=July 18, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Stylistic trademarks include brightly colored and textured surfaces with structure at many scales, and composite materials whose hardness, color, and shape vary over an object.  The results are often designed to be worn or touched, and inspired by nature and biology.\n\nMany of Oxman's projects use 3D printing and fabrication techniques.  They include the ''Silk Pavilion'', spun by silkworms released onto a nylon frame,<ref name=\"pavilion\">[http://www.dezeen.com/2013/06/03/silkworms-and-robot-work-together-to-weave-silk-pavilion/ Silkworms and Robot work together to weave silk pavilion], Dezeen, June 3, 2013.</ref> ''Ocean Pavilion'', a water-based fabrication platform that built structures out of [[chitosan]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Mogas-Soldevila|first=Laia |last2=Duro-Royo|first2=Jorge |last3=Lizardo|first3=Daniel |last4=Kayser|first4=Markus |last5=Patrick|first5= William |last6=Sharma|first6=Sunanda |last7=Keating|first7=Steven |last8=Klein|first8=John |last9=Inamura|first9=Chikara |last10=Oxman|first10=Neri |date=2015|title=DESIGNING THE OCEAN PAVILION: Biomaterial Templating of Structural, Manufacturing, and Environmental Performance|url=http://www.materialecology.com/assets/pdf/IASS2015_MediatedMatter_small.pdf|journal=Proceedings of the International Association for Shell and Spatial Structures (IASS) Symposium|volume=|issue=|doi=|access-date=September 16, 2016|via=}}</ref> \n''G3DP'', the first 3D printer for optically transparent glass and a set of glasswork produced by it,<ref>The G3DP [http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/g3dp Environment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805200420/http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/g3dp |date=August 5, 2018 }}, from the Mediated Matter Lab.</ref> \nand collections of 3D-printed clothing and wearables worn in couture shows and performances.<ref name=\"bjork\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2016/06/bjork-performed-worlds-first-360-vr-stream/|title=Bj\u00f6rk to perform the world's first 360 VR stream \u2013 Dancing Astronaut|date=June 28, 2016|website=Dancing Astronaut|language=en-US|access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe has held exhibitions at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] and Boston's [[Museum of Science (Boston)|Museum of Science]], which have some of her works in their permanent collections. [[MoMA]] curator [[Paola Antonelli]] called her \"a person ahead of her time, not of her time\",<ref name=\"surface\">{{cite web|url=http://www.surfacemag.com/articles/neri-oxman-material-ecology |title=Neri Oxman Is Redesigning the Natural World |publisher=[[Surface Magazine]] |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> \nand [[Bruce Sterling]] called her work \"shatteringly different from anything before\".<ref name=\"abitare\">{{cite news|title=Neri Oxman weaves nature's logic into design and makes buildings, architects, and Bruce Sterling sweat | last=Sterling|first=Bruce|date=May 1, 2008|work=ABITARE Magazine}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[File:RivkaOxman.jpg|thumb|[[Rivka Oxman]], mother of Neri Oxman and professor at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]]]]\nOxman was born and raised in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], to a Jewish family.<ref name=\"Ashley Baylen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/16982/top-50-hottest-jewish-women-10-1--page2/|title=Top 50 Hottest Jewish Women (10\u20131) \u2013 Page2|date=April 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107055137/http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/16982/top-50-hottest-jewish-women-10-1--page2/|archive-date=January 7, 2016|url-status=|publisher=Shalom Life|author=Ashley Baylen|accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"esquire.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a26279/new-wonder-woman-gal-gadot/|title=Who the Hell Is Your New Wonder Woman?|date=December 4, 2013|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Her parents, Robert and [[Rivka Oxman]], are both architects. Her younger sister, Keren Oxman, is an artist. Oxman graduated from the [[Hebrew Reali School]] in Haifa in 1994. Oxman grew up \"between nature and culture\", spending time in her grandmother's garden and her parent's architectural studio.\n\nAs with most Israeli youth, Neri Oxman served in the armed forces, enlisting in the [[Israeli Air Force]] from 1996 to 1999, achieving the rank of [[first lieutenant]]. After her service, she moved to [[Jerusalem]] to enter [[Hebrew University]]'s [[Hadassah Medical Center|Hadassah Medical School]]. After two years, she switched to studying architecture at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]], and then at the London [[Architectural Association School of Architecture]], graduating in 2004.<ref>Her master's thesis was on using \"structural, spatial and environmental\" cues to drive shape generation.\nOxman, Neri (2004). ''Performative Morphologies.''http://neri.media.mit.edu/assets/pdf/Publications_VH.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2005, she moved to Boston to join the architecture PhD program at [[MIT]], under adviser [[William J. Mitchell]]. Her thesis was on material-aware design.<ref name=\"thesis\">[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/59192 Material-based design computation], Neri Oxman, 2010. DSpace@MIT.</ref> In 2010, she became an associate professor at MIT in the MIT Media Lab as the Sony Corporation Career Development Professor (so named as the position is funded with a grant from [[Sony]]).\n\nOxman was previously married to Argentine composer [[Osvaldo Golijov]].<ref name=\"surface\"/> She  married [[Bill Ackman]] in January 2019.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/19/fashion/weddings/as-if-by-design-their-connection-was-inevitable.html]</ref> Oxman and Ackman have a child together.<ref name=\"Mallozzi\">{{cite web |title=As If by Design, Their Connection Was Inevitable|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/19/fashion/weddings/as-if-by-design-their-connection-was-inevitable.html |last=Mallozzi|first=Vincent|date=January 19, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Neri Oxman and Chuck Hoberman.jpg|Neri Oxman with [[Chuck Hoberman]] of [[Harvard Graduate School of Design ]]|thumb]]\nOxman's work has been displayed around the world, with pieces in the permanent collections of the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[Cooper Hewitt Design Museum]], the [[Centre Georges Pompidou]], Vienna's [[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|Museum of Applied Arts]], [[SFMOMA]], and Boston's [[Boston Museum of Fine Arts|Museum of Fine Arts]] and [[Boston Museum of Science|Museum of Science]].<ref name=\"oxmanlab\" />  Exhibits have also been shown at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum|Smithsonian]], and the Beijing International Art Biennale.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/ad.1110|title=Structuring Materiality: Design Fabrication of Heterogeneous Materials \u2013 Oxman \u2013 2010 \u2013 Architectural Design \u2013 Wiley Online Library |journal=Architectural Design |volume=80 |issue=4 |pages=78\u201385 |date=July 8, 2010|last1=Oxman |first1=Neri }}</ref>\n\nShe published papers on parametric and contextual design, and developed specific engineering techniques to realize those designs in various materials. In 2006, she launched an interdisciplinary research project at MIT called ''materialecology,'' to experiment with generative design.<ref>[https://materialecology.blogspot.com/ Material Ecology blog], 2006\u20132013</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.materialecology.com/|title=Material Ecology projects Neri Oxman|first=Neri|last=Oxman|publisher=}}</ref> This project and related collaborations informed her early art. She has promoted the idea of finding new ways to communicate about and collaborate on design.  In 2016, she helped launch the open multidisciplinary ''Journal of Design Science''.<ref>[https://www.wired.com/2016/03/mit-media-labs-journal-design-science-radical-new-kind-publication/ MIT Media Lab's Journal of Design Science], Liz Stinson, WIRED. March 10, 2016.</ref>\n\nShe has appeared on the covers of ''Fast Company'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3018964/most-creative-people-2009/73-neri-oxman|title=Most Creative People of 2009|last=|first=|date=2010|website=|publisher=Fast Company|access-date=}}</ref> ''Wired UK'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3dprintingindustry.com/news/wired-are-3d-printing-obsessed-1796/|title=The Team at Wired are 3D Printing Obsessed|access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> ''ICON'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iconeye.com/design/features/item/9917-neri-oxman-on-3d-printing|title=Neri Oxman on 3D Printing \u2013 Icon Magazine|last=O'Neal|first=Paul|date=|website=www.iconeye.com|publisher=|access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> and ''Surface'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shop.surfacemag.com/issues/no129|title=NO. 129 JUNE/JULY 2016|website=SURFACE|access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref> Her work is mentioned as an inspiration for changing how materials and structures are designed, and her artistic works were described by [[Andrew Bolton (curator)|Andrew Bolton]] as \"otherworldly\u2014defined by neither time nor place\".<ref>Sullivan, Robert. \u201cFuture Perfect\u201d, in ''VOGUE'', Met Gala Special Edition, June 2016, pp. 44\u201345.</ref>\n\nOn becoming a professor in 2010, Oxman founded the Mediated Matter research group at the MIT Media Lab.  There she expanded her collaborations into biology, medicine and wearables.\n\nIn 2019 it was revealed that her lab received $125,000 from financier and convicted sex offender [[Jeffrey Epstein]] through the MIT Media Lab and its director [[Joi Ito]].  She directed her students in the lab to send Epstein a gift despite the concerns about Epstein they brought to her attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/09/13/meeting-with-epstein-led-gift-and-now-regrets/0SPYm0hSg8iNh3JdDwPICP/story.html|title=A meeting with Jeffrey Epstein led to a gift \u2014 and, now, regrets - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Design philosophy ===\nOxman writes about the world and environment as organisms, changing regularly and responding to use, full of gradients of color and physical properties rather than sharp boundaries.  She proposed developing a material ecology with \"holistic products, characterized by property gradients and multi-functionality\" \u2013 in contrast to assembly lines and \u201ca world made of parts\".  On the interplay between design and fabrication methods, she said \"the assumption that parts are made from single materials and fulfill predetermined functions is deeply rooted in design... [and] enforced by the way that industrial supply chains work.\u201d<ref name=\"tedtalk\">[https://www.ted.com/talks/neri_oxman_design_at_the_intersection_of_technology_and_biology Design at the Intersection of Technology and Biology], 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Neri Oxman - Pop!Tech 2009 - Camden, ME.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Oxman at Pop!Tech 2009|left]]\n\nShe describes her work as pursuing \"a shift from ''consuming'' nature as a geological resource to ''editing'' it as a biological one.\"<ref name=\"weforum\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/07/tech/printing-3d-buildings-five-tenets-of-a-new-kind-of-architecture/index.html|title=Five Tenets of a New Kind of Architecture|last=Oxman|first=Neri|date=December 7, 2012|website=|publisher=CNN|access-date=}}</ref>  This leads to using mutli-scale biological shapes and textures for inspiration, and including living elements in fabrication processes, such as the glowing bacteria in ''Mushtari'' and using silkworms to construct the ''Silk Pavilion''.<ref name=\"pavilion\" />\nShe has written that science, engineering, design and art should be more actively connected \u2013 with the output of each discipline serving as input for another.<ref>[http://jods.mitpress.mit.edu/pub/AgeOfEntanglement The Age of Entangelement], Neri Oxman, Journal of Design and Science. January 13, 2016.</ref>\n\nOxman has given presentations on digital and cross-disciplinary design, and on moving beyond mass-produced design elements.  These included a presentation on form generation and environmental design,<ref>[https://vimeo.com/7806194 On Designing Form], PopTech 2009.</ref> cited by rapid prototypers in other fields,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Medical Modelling: The Application of Advanced Design and Rapid Prototyping Techniques in Medicine|last=Bibb|first=Richard|publisher=Woodhead Publishing|year=2015|isbn=9781782423003|location=|pages=313, 332|via=}}</ref> and a popular TED talk on designing \"at the intersection of technology and biology\".<ref name=\"tedtalk\" /> Her 2016 keynote at the [[American Institute of Architects]] conference proposed \"a more profound role for architecture in society\", by working hand-in-hand with science and engineering.<ref>[http://architosh.com/2016/06/perspectives-on-best-of-show-2016-from-edge-of-market-to-maturing-bim-framing-a-new-lens/ \"Perspectives on BEST of SHOW 2016\"], Architosh, June 3, 2016. The talk proposed \"a more profound role for the architecture field in society\", and received a standing ovation.</ref>\n\nOxman has used raycounting in her work, a technique that is the opposite of photo sculpting. In raycounting a flat surface is conversed into a highly curved one through a specific layout of light parameters. An algorithm calculates the intensity, position, and direction of one or multiple light sources placed in a given environment and assigns local curvature values to the relation between geometry and light performance. Then produced by stereolithography, the three double layered, translucent objects show resin pockets wherever these surfaces intersected.<ref>Sterling, Bruce. \u201cNatural\u2019 3-D Objects.\u201d Abitare, Edited by Anniina Koivu , no. 482, May 2008, pp. 134\u2013137.</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Neri's Inspirations and Impact on Young Women In Materials Sciences. ==\nOxman's works tie together fantastical approaches of the humanities with the sciences and engineering. What's most fantastic is her particular ability to tie different cultures together in her work. Her radically interdisciplinary approaches and writings have inspired young women in the field of engineering to take an immensely creative approach to design. She describes her approach for the glass structures that her and her team created for Lexus \"formalism with a moral compass\", she states how beauty is a sign of usefulness. This depth of character and absolute wonder that she brings into materials and the study of the natural world continues to strike inspiration and genius into the hearts of young ambitious engineers who deeply admire her work. {{clear|left}}\n== Television appearances ==\nOxman is the focus of an episode of Netflix docu-series [[Abstract: The Art of Design]] (season 2, episode 2).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/09/20/netflix-abstract-the-art-of-design-2-olafur-eliasson/|title=Neri Oxman and Olafur Eliasson feature in second series of Netflix design documentary|date=2019-09-20|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Mediated Matter ==\nThe Mediated Matter group uses computational design, digital fabrication, materials science and synthetic biology to explore design possibilities in small and large structures.<ref name=\"oxmanlab\">{{cite web|url=https://www.media.mit.edu/research/groups/mediated-matter  |title=Mediated Matter group website |publisher=MIT Media Lab |date= |accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"weforum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/01/towards-a-material-ecology/|title=What if our buildings were grown, not built?|author=Neri Oxman|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref>  This sometimes involved taking images of a biological sample, developing algorithms to produce similar structures, and developing new manufacturing processes to realize the results.\nProjects have included wearables inspired by current and future environments,<ref>[https://www.wired.com/2012/05/design-fiction-neri-oxman-imaginary-beings-mythologies-of-the-not-yet/ Design Fiction: Neri Oxman, \u201cImaginary Beings: Mythologies of the Not Yet\u201d], Wired magazine. May 12, 2012</ref>\nsolar-powered and biodegradable designs,<ref name=\"mushtari\">[http://www.archdaily.com/769818/neri-oxmans-mushtari-is-a-3d-printed-wearable-that-makes-products-from-sunlight \u201cMushtari\u201d Is a 3D Printed Wearable That Makes Products from Sunlight], ArchDaily. July 12, 2015</ref> new artistic techniques,\nand experimental surfaces, walls, coverings and load-bearing elements. Some of these involved combining work from many fields.\n\n=== Organic and natural fabrication ===\nA number of Oxman's works have involved fabrication by animals or by natural processes.\n\nThe ''Silk Pavilion'', an installation designed in 2013, was noted for its fabrication method as much as its final form.  It was woven by 6,500 free-ranging silkworms on a nylon-frame dome.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://www.materialecology.com/assets/pdf/Conf_FABRICATE_ArticleOxmanLaucks.pdf|title=Fabricate: Negotiating Design and Making|last=Oxman|first=Neri|last2=Laucks|first2=Jared|last3=Kayser|first3=Markus|display-authors=etal|publisher=gta Verlag|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=249\u2013255|chapter=Silk Pavilion: A case study in fibre-based digital fabrication}}</ref>  Experiments with the silkworms identified how they would respond to different surfaces, and what would encourage them to spin onto an existing structure rather than spinning a cocoon.  The frame of a large polyhedral dome was loosely woven by a robotic arm out of thin nylon threads, and suspended in an open room.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/thousands-of-silkworms-and-one-robot-made-this-intricat-511217252|title=Thousands of silkworms and one robot made this intricate sculpture|last=Dvorsky|first=George|work=io9|access-date=March 19, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>  The dome was designed with gaps where it would be warmest.  Silkworms were released onto the frame in waves, where they added layers of silk before being removed.  This involved engineering, [[sericulture]], and modelling sun in the room.  The resulting installation art was hung so that people could stand inside it.\n\nThe ''Ocean Pavilion,'' an installation from 2014, included a water-based fabrication platform where structures were built out of chitosan, a water-soluble organic fiber similar to chitin.  Structural pillars and long delicate leaves were made by varying how the fibers were deposited. The result was a combination of hard and soft structures, changing from solid to willowy over the length of a branch or leaf, but all made from the same base material.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ''Synthetic Apiary'', a room-sized installation built in 2015, studied the behavior of bees in an entirely indoor environment, including how they built hives in and around different structures.  This was developed in collaboration with a beekeeping company, as a way of testing possible responses to colony loss, and exploring how biological niches could be explicitly integrated into buildings.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.archdaily.com/796769/neri-oxman-plus-mediated-matter-create-synthetic-apiaries-to-combat-honeybee-colony-loss|title=Neri Oxman + Mediated Matter Create Synthetic Apiary to Combat Honeybee Colony Loss|date=October 5, 2016|newspaper=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 3D printing developments ===\nMediated Matter worked extensively with various 3D printing techniques, developing their own methods and collaborating with printing companies such as [[Stratasys]].  Projects have ranged in scale from enclosures and large furniture, to artwork and clothes, to biocomposites, artificial valves, and DNA assembly. The group designed a prototype printer with a robotic arm that could build 8-foot tall structures all around itself in outdoor spaces, and a quick-curing printer that makes free-standing objects without support structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://matter.media.mit.edu/publications/article/freeform-3d-printing-towards-a-sustainable-approach-to-additive-manufacturi|title=Freeform 3D Printing: Towards a Sustainable Approach to Additive Manufacturing|last=|first=|date=2013|website=|access-date=March 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302113304/http://matter.media.mit.edu/publications/article/freeform-3d-printing-towards-a-sustainable-approach-to-additive-manufacturi|archive-date=March 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Oxman printed her first set of body-sized wearables, a collection titled ''Imaginary Beings'' and inspired by legendary creatures.  This was followed by ''Anthozoa'', a dress developed in collaboration with fashion designer [[Iris van Herpen]] and materials engineer Craig Carter. These were some of the first examples of multi-color and multi-material 3D printing a human scale,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.3dprinter.net/the-not-so-secret-stratasys-objet-multi-color-3d-printer|title=The not-so-secret Objet multi-color 3D printer|last=|first=|date=May 7, 2012|work=3D Printer|access-date=February 28, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> using a bright palette with fine granular control of color and texture.  In 2015, she designed the ''Wanderers'' collection with Christoph Bader and Dominik Kolb, inspired by ideas of interplanetary exploration. That earned Fast Company's award for Design Innovation. The most influential of the Wanderers was the ''Living Mushtari'' chestpiece, a model digestive tract filled with liquid and a colony of photosynthetic [[Cyanobacteria|bacteria]] and ''[[E. coli]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/mit-professor-creates-3d-printed-wearable-skin-space-exploration-1477862|title=MIT professor creates 3D printed 'wearable skin' for space exploration|date=December 3, 2014|access-date=August 7, 2016}}</ref>  Producing ''Mushtari'' required new modeling methods for printing long flexible tubes with varying thickness.\n\nIn 2016, she produced ''Rottlace,'' a set of 3D-printed feathered, filamented, and textured masks.  These were made for the artist [[Bj\u00f6rk]],<ref>From \"Ro\u00f0laus\", Icelandic for \"skinless\".</ref> based on a 3D scan of her face. Bj\u00f6rk wore these in the world's first 360\u00b0 VR performance.<ref name=\"bjork\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dentsulab.tokyo/events/20160628/|title=Making of Bj\u00f6rk Digital|last=|first=|date=|access-date=February 28, 2017|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423212441/http://dentsulab.tokyo/events/20160628|archive-date=April 23, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  She also began designing ''Vespers'', a collection of 15 death masks. Described as \"like something out of ''Alien''\", each mask is a curved translucent shell the size of a face, within which a detailed pattern is printed in clouds of color and shadow. This tested the limits of how small voxels of color could be inside a 3D printed solid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/gallery/death-masks-neri-oxman-vesper|title=Haunting 3D-printed death masks are like something out of Alien|work=WIRED UK|access-date=March 10, 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"vespers\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/vespers-the-latest-mask-collection-by-mits-neri-oxman_o|title=Vespers, the Latest Mask Collection by MIT's Neri Oxman|date=December 15, 2016|work=Architect|access-date=March 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOxman has also premiered new printing tools and processes. In 2015, she designed ''Gemini'', a large chaise lounge combining a milled wood shell with a 3D-printed surface.  Both the outer shell and the texture of the inner surface were designed to produce a soothing acoustical environment for someone reclining in it. ''Gemini'' was later acquired by [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SF MoMA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3dprintingindustry.com/news/neri-oxman-pursues-3d-printing-multi-materials-latest-mythical-installation-gemini-25368/|title=Neri Oxman Further Pursues 3D Printing with Multi-Materials for her Latest Mythical Installation \u2014 \"GEMINI\"|access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Matter-glass-printer.webm|thumb|The ''G3DP'' glass printing process]]\nAlso in 2015, a Mediated Matter team developed ''G3DP'',<ref>{{Cite book|title=Additive Manufacturing of Optically Transparent Glass|last=Klein|first=John|publisher=Mediated Matter|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> the first 3D printer for optically transparent glass.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2015/3-d-printing-transparent-glass-0914|title=Printing transparent glass in 3-D|last=Chandler|first=David|date=September 14, 2015|work=MIT News|access-date=July 9, 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://singularityhub.com/2015/09/09/watch-mits-breakthrough-3d-printer-pour-molten-glass-like-honey/|title=Watch MIT's Breakthrough 3D Printer Pour Molten Glass Like Honey|last=Dorrier|first=Jason|date=September 9, 2015|website=Singularity Hub|publisher=Singularity University|access-date=August 1, 2016}}</ref> At the time, sintering 3D printers could print with glass powder, but the results were brittle and opaque.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.shapeways.com/blog/archives/401-you-can-now-3d-print-in-glass-with-shapeways.html|title=you can now 3D print in glass with Shapeways|last=joris|date=April 14, 2010|work=The Shapeways Blog|access-date=March 19, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> ''G3DP'' was designed in collaboration with MIT's Glass Lab and the [[Wyss Institute for Biologically Inspired Engineering|Wyss Institute]], emulating traditional glass working processes. Molten glass was poured in fine streams and cooled in an annealing chamber, yielding precision suitable for [[Glass art|art]] and consumer products, and glass strength suitable for [[Architectural glass|architectural]] elements.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://optics.org/news/6/9/3|title=US group develops 3D-printing technique for optical glass|last=Peach|first=Matthew|date=September 1, 2015|website=optics.org|publisher=SPIE|access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> The process allowed close control of color, transparency, thickness and texture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/mits-neri-oxman-on-the-true-beauty-of-3d-printed-glass_o|title=MIT's Neri Oxman on the True Beauty of 3D Printed Glass|date=August 28, 2015|access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> Changing the height and speed of the nozzle produced uniform loops, turning the printer into a \"molden glass sewing machine\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-35171408|title='Sewing' with molten glass and maths|last=Webb|first=Jonathan|date=January 1, 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=March 19, 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> A set of glass vessels made with this printer went on exhibit at the Cooper Hewitt and other museums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooperhewitt.org/events/current-exhibitions/beauty-cooper-hewitt-design-triennial/ |title=Cooper Hewitt Design Triennial, ''Beauty'' |date=July 2016|publisher=Cooper Hewitt}}</ref> and a 10-foot tall sculpture of light and printed glass, ''YET'', was designed for the 2017 Milan Design Week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.linformatique.org/exposition-lexus-yet-milan-design-week-neri-oxman.html|title=L'exposition \" Lexus Yet \" \u00e0 la Milan Design Week en collaboration avec Neri Oxman {{!}} Linformatique.org|last=Manon|first=Victoria|date=February 17, 2017|work=Linformatique.org|access-date=February 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217182418/http://www.linformatique.org/exposition-lexus-yet-milan-design-week-neri-oxman.html|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=dead|language=fr-FR}}</ref>\n\n== Publications and essays ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n* 2016: What if our buildings were grown, not built?<ref name=\"weforum\"/>\n* 2015: Material Ecology<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|last2=Ortiz|first2=Christine|last3=Gramazio|first3=Fabio|last4=Kohler|first4=Matthias|date=March 1, 2015|title=Material ecology|journal=Computer-Aided Design|series=Material Ecology|volume=60|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2014.05.009|hdl=1721.1/107168|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2014: Gemini: <small>Multi-Material Digital Design Fabrication</small><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|last2=Dikovsky|first2=Daniel|last3=Belocon|first3=Boris|last4=Carter|first4=W. Craig|date=September 1, 2014|title=Gemini: Engaging Experiential and Feature Scales Through Multimaterial Digital Design and Hybrid Additive\u2013Subtractive Fabrication|journal=3D Printing and Additive Manufacturing|volume=1|issue=3|pages=108\u2013114|doi=10.1089/3dp.2014.1505|issn=2329-7662|hdl=1721.1/108169|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2011: Variable Property Rapid Prototyping<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|date=March 1, 2011|title=Variable property rapid prototyping|journal=Virtual and Physical Prototyping|volume=6|issue=1|pages=3\u201331|doi=10.1080/17452759.2011.558588|issn=1745-2759}}</ref>\n* 2006: Tropisms: <small>Computing Theoretical Morphospaces of Branching Growth Systems</small><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|date=2006|title=Collective Intelligence in Design, pg 20.|url=|journal=AD (Architectural Design)|volume=76|issue=5|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|right}}\n'''Group publications'''\n* 2016: 3D Printed Multimaterial Microfluidic Valve<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keating|first=Steven J.|last2=Gariboldi|first2=Maria Isabella|last3=Patrick|first3=William G.|last4=Sharma|first4=Sunanda|last5=Kong|first5=David S.|last6=Oxman|first6=Neri|date=August 15, 2016|title=3D Printed Multimaterial Microfluidic Valve|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=11|issue=8|pages=e0160624|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0160624|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4985141|pmid=27525809|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1160624K}}</ref>\n* 2016: DNA Assembly in 3D Printed Fluidics<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patrick|first=William G.|last2=Nielsen|first2=Alec A. K.|last3=Keating|first3=Steven J.|last4=Levy|first4=Taylor J.|last5=Wang|first5=Che-Wei|last6=Rivera|first6=Jaime J.|last7=Mondrag\u00f3n-Palomino|first7=Octavio|last8=Carr|first8=Peter A.|last9=Voigt|first9=Christopher A.; Oxman, Neri; Kong, David S.|date=December 30, 2015|title=DNA Assembly in 3D Printed Fluidics|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0143636|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0143636|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4699221|pmid=26716448|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1043636P}}</ref>\n* 2015: Flow-based Fabrication<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Duro-Royo|first=Jorge|last2=Mogas-Soldevila|first2=Laia|last3=Oxman|first3=Neri|date=December 1, 2015|title=Flow-based fabrication: An integrated computational workflow for design and digital additive manufacturing of multifunctional heterogeneously structured objects|journal=Computer-Aided Design|volume=69|pages=143\u2013154|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2015.05.005|hdl=1721.1/112152|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2015: Additive Manufacturing of Optically Transparent Glass<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=John|last2=Stern|first2=Michael|last3=Franchin|first3=Giorgia|last4=Kayser|first4=Markus|last5=Inamura|first5=Chikara|last6=Dave|first6=Shreya|last7=Weaver|first7=James C.|last8=Houk|first8=Peter|last9=Colombo|first9=Paolo; Yang, Maria; Oxman, Neri|date=August 19, 2015|title=Additive Manufacturing of Optically Transparent Glass|journal=3D Printing and Additive Manufacturing|volume=2|issue=3|pages=92\u2013105|doi=10.1089/3dp.2015.0021|issn=2329-7662|pmid=|hdl=1721.1/101831|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Exhibited works==\nOxman's early projects took the form of example surfaces, furniture, or objects that could be worn or put on display.  Most were exhibited in museums.  More recent work included temporary and interactive installations.  Some, such as the ''Ocean Pavilion'' and ''G3DP,'' included a production process;<ref name=\":2\" /> others, such as the ''Silk Pavilion'' and ''Synthetic Apiary,'' included biological observation and research on the exhibit.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Selected works ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''Cartesian Wax'',  ''Monocoque'',  ''Subterrain''<ref>''Variable Property Analysis and Fabrication of a Butterfly Wing''</ref> (2007, [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://neri.media.mit.edu/projects|title=Project list|last=|first=|date=|website=Personal site|publisher=MIT Media Lab|access-date=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Raycounting'', ''Penumbra'' (2007, MoMA)\n* ''Fibonacci\u2019s Mashrabiya'' (2009, 12, [[Centre Georges Pompidou|Centre Pompidou]])\n* ''Beast: <small>Prototype for a Chaise Longue</small>'' (2010, MoS)\n* ''Carpal Skin''<ref>''Prototype for a Carpal Tunnel Syndrome Splint''</ref> (2010, [[Museum of Science (Boston)|Museum of Science]])\n* ''Silk Pavilion'' (2012), installation \n* ''<u>Imaginary Beings</u>'' (2012, Centre Pompidou)\n** 18 'wearables for demigods': ''Gravida'', ''Pneuma'', ''Remora''\n{{clear|right}}\n[[File:G3DP glass bowl-sm.png|thumb|upright=0.4|right|''G3DP'' bowl]]\n* ''Ocean Pavilion'' (2013), installation\n* ''Anthozoa'' (2013, [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|MFA]]), couture dress\n* ''Gemini'' (2015, [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SF MoMA]]), acoustical chaise\n* ''<u>Wanderers</u>'' collection (2015):<ref>[https://3dprint.com/26925/wearable-skins-triple-jetting/ Wearable skins], Sarah Anderson Goehrke. 3DPrint.com, November 25, 2014.</ref>\n** ''Otaared'', ''Qamar'', ''Zuhai''\n** ''Living Mushtari''\n* ''G3DP'' (2015), 3D printer & glasswork\n* ''Synthetic Apiary'' (2015), installation<ref>[http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/synthetic-apiary Synthetic apiary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817093154/http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/synthetic-apiary |date=August 17, 2018 }}: a perpetual spring environment.  Retrieved September 15, 2016</ref>\n* ''Rottlace'' (2016, Bj\u00f6rk), masks<ref name=\"bjork\"/>\n* ''Vespers'' (2016\u20132018), death mask series<ref name=\"vespers\"/>\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Gallery ===\n\n; Art, surfaces, and furniture\n<gallery>\nFile:Neri Oxman CartesianWax 03.tif|''Cartesian Wax'' surface\nFile:Monocoque-2010-moma.jpg|''Monocoque 2'', [[MoMA]]\nFile:Oxman Raycounting-10 MoMA.tiff|''Raycounting'', multiply lit\nFile:Pneuma 2 by Neri Oxman at the 3D, printing the future exhibition at the Science Museum, London.JPG|''Pneuma 2''\nFile:Caustic patterns of a 3D printed glass structure.jpg|''G3DP'' printed glasswork\n</gallery>\n\n; Wearables, machines, and installations\n<gallery>\nFile:NeriOxman-VanHerpenShow.jpg|''Anthozoa'' dress\nFile:Matter-glass-printer.webm|''G3DP'' printing process\nFile:GLASS_II_-_Mediated_Matter.webm|2d gen G3DP\nFile:Matter-silk-pavilion.webm|Silk Pavilion process\nFile:Synthetic-apiary.webm|Synthetic Apiary studies\nFile:Mushtari.webm|''Mushtari'' living corset\nFile:Oxman-wanderers-morphology.jpg|Family of morphologies used for ''Wanderers''\nFile:Vespers_Series_III_-_Mediated_Matter.webm|Vespers death masks\n</gallery>\n\n=== Selected exhibits ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Beijing International Art Biennale|Beijing Art Biennale]]: 2006\u20132010\n*[[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]], New York: 2007, 2010 (<small>''Action: Design over Time''</small>), 2015 (<small>''This Is for Everyone''</small>)\n*[[Museum of Science (Boston)|Museum of Science]], Boston: 2012 (<small>''Neri Oxman:'' ''At the Frontier of Ecological Design''</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mos.org/sites/dev-elvis.mos.org/files/docs/advancement/mos_magazine_fall-2009.pdf|title=Neri Oxman: At the Frontier of Ecological Design|last=|first=|date=Fall 2009|website=|publisher=Museum of Science, Boston|access-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref>)\n*[[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|Cooper Hewitt Museum]]: 2015 (<small>''Making Design''</small>), 2016 (<small>''Beauty''</small>)\n*[[Centre Georges Pompidou|Centre Pompidou]], Paris: 2012  (<small>''Imaginary Beings'' exhibit, ''Multiversit\u00e9s Cr\u00e9atives''</small><ref>[https://www.wired.com/2012/05/design-fiction-neri-oxman-imaginary-beings-mythologies-of-the-not-yet/ Imaginary Beings: Mythologies of the Not Yet], ''Wired'', May 2012.</ref>)\n*[[Science Museum, London]]: 2012 & 2013 (<small>''3D PRINT SHOW''</small><ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2013/mar/10/entertainment/la-et-cm-3d-print-show-20130310 3-D printing produces a fresh creative outlet for artists],  L.J. Williamson, LA Times. March 10, 2013.</ref>)\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|Museum of Fine Arts]], Boston: 2013, 2016 (<small>''#techstyle: Production''</small><ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/2016/03/07/what-future-fashion-mfa-techstyle-show-looks-for-answers/s5lyjSDP4V89aG9cQpEhVM/story.html What is the future of fashion?], Joe Incollingo, Boston Globe. March 7, 2016.</ref>)\n*[[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|Museum of Applied Arts]], Vienna: 2014 (<small>''150 Years of the MAK''</small><ref>[http://blog.mak.at/remora-exemplary-150-years-of-the-mak-from-arts-and-crafts-to-design/ Remora \u2013 EXEMPLARY: 150 YEARS OF THE MAK], MAK Blog. July 8, 2014.</ref>)\n*[[National Gallery of Victoria]], Victoria: 2017 (<small>''NGV Triennial''</small><ref>[http://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/the+ngv+announces+its+biggest+installation+of+the+year,42127 The NGV announces its biggest installation of the year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003142324/http://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/the+ngv+announces+its+biggest+installation+of+the+year,42127 |date=October 3, 2017 }}, Angelica Xidias. ''[[Vogue Magazine]]'', March 8, 2017.</ref>)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nOxman is a senior fellow in the [[Design Futures Council]], and won the [[The Vilcek Foundation|Vilcek Prize]] in Design in 2014.<ref name=\"vilcek\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.mit.edu/2014/media-labs-neri-oxman-awarded-vilcek-prize-|title=Media Lab's Neri Oxman awarded Vilcek Prize|website=MIT News|accessdate=November 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she was on ICON\u2019s list of the \u201c20 Most Influential Architects to Shape Our Future.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Architect, Designer Neri Oxman Uses Principles of Nature to Create, Build|last=|first=|date=November 3, 2010|work=|publisher=Targeted News Service|access-date=|via=}}</ref>  In 2012, ''Shalom Life'' ranked her number 1 on its list of \u201cmost talented, intelligent, funny, and gorgeous Jewish women in the world.\"<ref name=\"Ashley Baylen\"/><ref name=\"esquire.com\"/>\n\nOther awards include:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[London Design Festival]] Design Innovation medal (2018)[https://www.londondesignfestival.com/design-innovation-medal-neri-oxman]\n* MIT [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology Police Department|Collier Medal]] (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrweb.mit.edu/rewards/recipient/award-recipients/2016/collier-medal/neri-oxman|title=2016 Collier Medal {{!}} Neri Oxman|last=|first=|date=|website=hrweb.mit.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-23}}</ref> \n* Cultural Leader, [[World Economic Forum]] (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://widgets.weforum.org/davos-arts/2016/|title=Arts and Culture at Davos 2016|website=widgets.weforum.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-23}}</ref> \n* Innovation by Design Award, [[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] (2015), for ''Wanderers''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/773938/neri-oxman-and-som-among-fast-companys-innovation-by-design-award-winners|title=Neri Oxman and SOM Among Fast Company's Innovation By Design Award Winners|date=September 18, 2015|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[American Institute of Architects]] Women in Design (2014)<ref>[http://abexpo.com/conference/women-in-design-symposium-the-value-of-design/women-in-design-2014-award-winners AIA Women in Design award winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815181830/http://abexpo.com/conference/women-in-design-symposium-the-value-of-design/women-in-design-2014-award-winners |date=August 15, 2016 }}, 2014</ref>\n* [[Carnegie Corporation|Carnegie]] \"Pride of America\" Award (2014)<ref>[http://greatimmigrants.carnegie.org/profile/neri-oxman/ Pride of America Honorees] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815203354/http://greatimmigrants.carnegie.org/profile/neri-oxman/ |date=August 15, 2016 }} page</ref>\n* [[Vilcek Foundation|Vilcek Prize]] in Design (2014)<ref name=\"vilcek\"/>\n* Senior Fellow, [[Design Futures Council]] (2013)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://designfuturescouncil.com/about/fellows/|title=Senior Fellows - Design Futures Council|work=Design Futures Council|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324174034/http://designfuturescouncil.com/about/fellows/|archivedate=March 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Earth Award for Future Crucial Design]] (2009)<ref>[http://bustler.net/news/684/fab-recology-designer-neri-oxman-named-winner-of-first-earth-award Neri Oxman named winner of first Earth Award], Bustler, January 13, 2009.</ref>\n* Carter Manny Citation, [[Graham Foundation for Advanced Studies in the Fine Arts|Graham Foundation for the Arts]] (2008)\n* [[LafargeHolcim Foundation for Sustainable Construction|Holcim Foundation]] Next Generation Award (2008), for \"microstructure research for building skins\"<ref>[https://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/Article/top-sustainable-construction-projects-in-north-america-honored \"Top sustainable construction projects in North America honored\"], Holcim Foundation</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://matter.media.mit.edu Official site]\n\n{{Portal bar|Architecture}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oxman, Neri}}\n[[Category:Israeli architects]]\n[[Category:Israeli designers]]\n[[Category:Israeli expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hebrew Reali School alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:People from Haifa]]\n[[Category:MIT Media Lab people]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Neri Oxman\n| birth_name         = \u05e0\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d5\u05e7\u05e1\u05de\u05df\u200e\n| native_name_lang   = he\n| image              = Neri Oxman by Noah Kalina.jpg\n| caption            = Oxman in 2017\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|02|06}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Design and the elastic mind|last=Antonelli|first=Paula|date=2008-01-01|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|isbn=9780870707322|location=NY, NY|pages=75|oclc=780473124}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Haifa]], Israel\n| nationality        = Israeli, American\n| alma_mater         = The [[Hebrew Reali School]] in Haifa, Israel <br /> [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]] (BA)<br />[[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]<br />[[Architectural Association School of Architecture|Architectural Association]] (MA)<br />[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (PhD)\n| occupation         = Associate professor of media arts and science<ref>{{cite web |url= http://singularityhub.com/2012/06/04/3d-printing-is-the-future-of-manufacturing-and-neri-oxman-shows-how-beautiful-it-can-be/ |title=3D Printing Is The Future Of Manufacturing And Neri Oxman Shows How Beautiful It Can Be|first= David J.|last= Hill|work=singularityhub.com |date= June 4, 2012|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>\n| notable_works      = ''Silk Pavilion'' (2013) <br /> ''Wanderers'' (2015) <br /> ''Material Ecology'' (2020)\n| awards             = [[Vilcek Prize]], 2014<br /> [[Earth Award for Future Crucial Design|Earth Award]], 2009\n| spouse             = [[Osvaldo Golijov]] (divorced)<br />[[Bill Ackman]] (2019\u2013present)<ref name=\"Mallozzi\">{{cite web |title=As If by Design, Their Connection Was Inevitable|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/19/fashion/weddings/as-if-by-design-their-connection-was-inevitable.html |last=Mallozzi|first=Vincent|date=January 19, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n| children           = 1 daughter\n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n   | allegiance      = {{flag|Israel}}\n   | branch          = [[File:Air Force Ensign of Israel.svg|21px]] [[Israeli Air Force]]\n   | serviceyears    = 1996-1999\n   | rank            = [[File:IAF segen.svg|16px]] [[First lieutenant]]\n}}\n}}\n<!-- end of infobox person -->\n\n'''Neri Oxman''' ({{lang-he|\u05e0\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d5\u05e7\u05e1\u05de\u05df}}; born 6 February 1976) is an [[American\u2013Israeli]] designer and professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] [[MIT Media Lab|Media Lab]], where she leads the Mediated Matter research group. She is known for art and architecture that combine design, biology, computing, and materials engineering.\n\nHer work embodies [[environmental design]] and [[digital morphogenesis]], with shapes and properties that are determined by their context.  She coined the phrase \"material ecology\" to define her work, placing materials in context.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.materialecology.com/|title=Material Ecology website|date=|publisher=|accessdate=October 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dirt.asla.org/2009/08/20/material-ecology/|title=Material Ecology|date=August 20, 2009|publisher=The Dirt|accessdate=April 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718021252/http://dirt.asla.org/2009/08/20/material-ecology/|archive-date=July 18, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Stylistic trademarks include brightly colored and textured surfaces with structure at many scales, and composite materials whose hardness, color, and shape vary over an object.  The results are often designed to be worn or touched, and inspired by nature and biology.\n\nMany of Oxman's projects use 3D printing and fabrication techniques.  They include the ''Silk Pavilion'', spun by silkworms released onto a nylon frame,<ref name=\"pavilion\">[http://www.dezeen.com/2013/06/03/silkworms-and-robot-work-together-to-weave-silk-pavilion/ Silkworms and Robot work together to weave silk pavilion], Dezeen, June 3, 2013.</ref> ''Ocean Pavilion'', a water-based fabrication platform that built structures out of [[chitosan]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Mogas-Soldevila|first=Laia |last2=Duro-Royo|first2=Jorge |last3=Lizardo|first3=Daniel |last4=Kayser|first4=Markus |last5=Patrick|first5= William |last6=Sharma|first6=Sunanda |last7=Keating|first7=Steven |last8=Klein|first8=John |last9=Inamura|first9=Chikara |last10=Oxman|first10=Neri |date=2015|title=DESIGNING THE OCEAN PAVILION: Biomaterial Templating of Structural, Manufacturing, and Environmental Performance|url=http://www.materialecology.com/assets/pdf/IASS2015_MediatedMatter_small.pdf|journal=Proceedings of the International Association for Shell and Spatial Structures (IASS) Symposium|volume=|issue=|doi=|access-date=September 16, 2016|via=}}</ref> \n''G3DP'', the first 3D printer for optically transparent glass and a set of glasswork produced by it,<ref>The G3DP [http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/g3dp Environment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805200420/http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/g3dp |date=August 5, 2018 }}, from the Mediated Matter Lab.</ref> \nand collections of 3D-printed clothing and wearables worn in couture shows and performances.<ref name=\"bjork\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2016/06/bjork-performed-worlds-first-360-vr-stream/|title=Bj\u00f6rk to perform the world's first 360 VR stream \u2013 Dancing Astronaut|date=June 28, 2016|website=Dancing Astronaut|language=en-US|access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe has held exhibitions at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] and Boston's [[Museum of Science (Boston)|Museum of Science]], which have some of her works in their permanent collections. [[MoMA]] curator [[Paola Antonelli]] called her \"a person ahead of her time, not of her time\",<ref name=\"surface\">{{cite web|url=http://www.surfacemag.com/articles/neri-oxman-material-ecology |title=Neri Oxman Is Redesigning the Natural World |publisher=[[Surface Magazine]] |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> \nand [[Bruce Sterling]] called her work \"shatteringly different from anything before\".<ref name=\"abitare\">{{cite news|title=Neri Oxman weaves nature's logic into design and makes buildings, architects, and Bruce Sterling sweat | last=Sterling|first=Bruce|date=May 1, 2008|work=ABITARE Magazine}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[File:RivkaOxman.jpg|thumb|[[Rivka Oxman]], mother of Neri Oxman and professor at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]]]]\nOxman was born and raised in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], to a Jewish family.<ref name=\"Ashley Baylen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/16982/top-50-hottest-jewish-women-10-1--page2/|title=Top 50 Hottest Jewish Women (10\u20131) \u2013 Page2|date=April 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107055137/http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/16982/top-50-hottest-jewish-women-10-1--page2/|archive-date=January 7, 2016|url-status=|publisher=Shalom Life|author=Ashley Baylen|accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"esquire.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a26279/new-wonder-woman-gal-gadot/|title=Who the Hell Is Your New Wonder Woman?|date=December 4, 2013|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Her parents, Robert and [[Rivka Oxman]], are both architects. Her younger sister, Keren Oxman, is an artist. Oxman graduated from the [[Hebrew Reali School]] in Haifa in 1994. Oxman grew up \"between nature and culture\", spending time in her grandmother's garden and her parent's architectural studio.\n\nAs with most Israeli youth, Neri Oxman served in the armed forces, enlisting in the [[Israeli Air Force]] from 1996 to 1999, achieving the rank of [[first lieutenant]]. After her service, she moved to [[Jerusalem]] to enter [[Hebrew University]]'s [[Hadassah Medical Center|Hadassah Medical School]]. After two years, she switched to studying architecture at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]], and then at the London [[Architectural Association School of Architecture]], graduating in 2004.<ref>Her master's thesis was on using \"structural, spatial and environmental\" cues to drive shape generation.\nOxman, Neri (2004). ''Performative Morphologies.''http://neri.media.mit.edu/assets/pdf/Publications_VH.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2005, she moved to Boston to join the architecture PhD program at [[MIT]], under adviser [[William J. Mitchell]]. Her thesis was on material-aware design.<ref name=\"thesis\">[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/59192 Material-based design computation], Neri Oxman, 2010. DSpace@MIT.</ref> In 2010, she became an associate professor at MIT in the MIT Media Lab as the Sony Corporation Career Development Professor (so named as the position is funded with a grant from [[Sony]]).\n\nOxman was previously married to Argentine composer [[Osvaldo Golijov]].<ref name=\"surface\"/> She  married [[Bill Ackman]] in January 2019.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/19/fashion/weddings/as-if-by-design-their-connection-was-inevitable.html]</ref> Oxman and Ackman have a child together.<ref name=\"Mallozzi\">{{cite web |title=As If by Design, Their Connection Was Inevitable|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/19/fashion/weddings/as-if-by-design-their-connection-was-inevitable.html |last=Mallozzi|first=Vincent|date=January 19, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Neri Oxman and Chuck Hoberman.jpg|Neri Oxman with [[Chuck Hoberman]] of [[Harvard Graduate School of Design ]]|thumb]]\nOxman's work has been displayed around the world, with pieces in the permanent collections of the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[Cooper Hewitt Design Museum]], the [[Centre Georges Pompidou]], Vienna's [[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|Museum of Applied Arts]], [[SFMOMA]], and Boston's [[Boston Museum of Fine Arts|Museum of Fine Arts]] and [[Boston Museum of Science|Museum of Science]].<ref name=\"oxmanlab\" />  Exhibits have also been shown at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum|Smithsonian]], and the Beijing International Art Biennale.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/ad.1110|title=Structuring Materiality: Design Fabrication of Heterogeneous Materials \u2013 Oxman \u2013 2010 \u2013 Architectural Design \u2013 Wiley Online Library |journal=Architectural Design |volume=80 |issue=4 |pages=78\u201385 |date=July 8, 2010|last1=Oxman |first1=Neri }}</ref>\n\nShe published papers on parametric and contextual design, and developed specific engineering techniques to realize those designs in various materials. In 2006, she launched an interdisciplinary research project at MIT called ''materialecology,'' to experiment with generative design.<ref>[https://materialecology.blogspot.com/ Material Ecology blog], 2006\u20132013</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.materialecology.com/|title=Material Ecology projects Neri Oxman|first=Neri|last=Oxman|publisher=}}</ref> This project and related collaborations informed her early art. She has promoted the idea of finding new ways to communicate about and collaborate on design.  In 2016, she helped launch the open multidisciplinary ''Journal of Design Science''.<ref>[https://www.wired.com/2016/03/mit-media-labs-journal-design-science-radical-new-kind-publication/ MIT Media Lab's Journal of Design Science], Liz Stinson, WIRED. March 10, 2016.</ref>\n\nShe has appeared on the covers of ''Fast Company'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3018964/most-creative-people-2009/73-neri-oxman|title=Most Creative People of 2009|last=|first=|date=2010|website=|publisher=Fast Company|access-date=}}</ref> ''Wired UK'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3dprintingindustry.com/news/wired-are-3d-printing-obsessed-1796/|title=The Team at Wired are 3D Printing Obsessed|access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> ''ICON'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iconeye.com/design/features/item/9917-neri-oxman-on-3d-printing|title=Neri Oxman on 3D Printing \u2013 Icon Magazine|last=O'Neal|first=Paul|date=|website=www.iconeye.com|publisher=|access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> and ''Surface'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shop.surfacemag.com/issues/no129|title=NO. 129 JUNE/JULY 2016|website=SURFACE|access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref> Her work is mentioned as an inspiration for changing how materials and structures are designed, and her artistic works were described by [[Andrew Bolton (curator)|Andrew Bolton]] as \"otherworldly\u2014defined by neither time nor place\".<ref>Sullivan, Robert. \u201cFuture Perfect\u201d, in ''VOGUE'', Met Gala Special Edition, June 2016, pp. 44\u201345.</ref>\n\nOn becoming a professor in 2010, Oxman founded the Mediated Matter research group at the MIT Media Lab.  There she expanded her collaborations into biology, medicine and wearables.\n\nIn 2019 it was revealed that her lab received $125,000 from financier and convicted sex offender [[Jeffrey Epstein]] through the MIT Media Lab and its director [[Joi Ito]].  She directed her students in the lab to send Epstein a gift despite the concerns about Epstein they brought to her attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/09/13/meeting-with-epstein-led-gift-and-now-regrets/0SPYm0hSg8iNh3JdDwPICP/story.html|title=A meeting with Jeffrey Epstein led to a gift \u2014 and, now, regrets - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Design philosophy ===\nOxman writes about the world and environment as organisms, changing regularly and responding to use, full of gradients of color and physical properties rather than sharp boundaries.  She proposed developing a material ecology with \"holistic products, characterized by property gradients and multi-functionality\" \u2013 in contrast to assembly lines and \u201ca world made of parts\".  On the interplay between design and fabrication methods, she said \"the assumption that parts are made from single materials and fulfill predetermined functions is deeply rooted in design... [and] enforced by the way that industrial supply chains work.\u201d<ref name=\"tedtalk\">[https://www.ted.com/talks/neri_oxman_design_at_the_intersection_of_technology_and_biology Design at the Intersection of Technology and Biology], 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Neri Oxman - Pop!Tech 2009 - Camden, ME.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Oxman at Pop!Tech 2009|left]]\n\nShe describes her work as pursuing \"a shift from ''consuming'' nature as a geological resource to ''editing'' it as a biological one.\"<ref name=\"weforum\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/07/tech/printing-3d-buildings-five-tenets-of-a-new-kind-of-architecture/index.html|title=Five Tenets of a New Kind of Architecture|last=Oxman|first=Neri|date=December 7, 2012|website=|publisher=CNN|access-date=}}</ref>  This leads to using mutli-scale biological shapes and textures for inspiration, and including living elements in fabrication processes, such as the glowing bacteria in ''Mushtari'' and using silkworms to construct the ''Silk Pavilion''.<ref name=\"pavilion\" />\nShe has written that science, engineering, design and art should be more actively connected \u2013 with the output of each discipline serving as input for another.<ref>[http://jods.mitpress.mit.edu/pub/AgeOfEntanglement The Age of Entangelement], Neri Oxman, Journal of Design and Science. January 13, 2016.</ref>\n\nOxman has given presentations on digital and cross-disciplinary design, and on moving beyond mass-produced design elements.  These included a presentation on form generation and environmental design,<ref>[https://vimeo.com/7806194 On Designing Form], PopTech 2009.</ref> cited by rapid prototypers in other fields,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Medical Modelling: The Application of Advanced Design and Rapid Prototyping Techniques in Medicine|last=Bibb|first=Richard|publisher=Woodhead Publishing|year=2015|isbn=9781782423003|location=|pages=313, 332|via=}}</ref> and a popular TED talk on designing \"at the intersection of technology and biology\".<ref name=\"tedtalk\" /> Her 2016 keynote at the [[American Institute of Architects]] conference proposed \"a more profound role for architecture in society\", by working hand-in-hand with science and engineering.<ref>[http://architosh.com/2016/06/perspectives-on-best-of-show-2016-from-edge-of-market-to-maturing-bim-framing-a-new-lens/ \"Perspectives on BEST of SHOW 2016\"], Architosh, June 3, 2016. The talk proposed \"a more profound role for the architecture field in society\", and received a standing ovation.</ref>\n\nOxman has used raycounting in her work, a technique that is the opposite of photo sculpting. In raycounting a flat surface is conversed into a highly curved one through a specific layout of light parameters. An algorithm calculates the intensity, position, and direction of one or multiple light sources placed in a given environment and assigns local curvature values to the relation between geometry and light performance. Then produced by stereolithography, the three double layered, translucent objects show resin pockets wherever these surfaces intersected.<ref>Sterling, Bruce. \u201cNatural\u2019 3-D Objects.\u201d Abitare, Edited by Anniina Koivu , no. 482, May 2008, pp. 134\u2013137.</ref>\n\n{{clear|left}}\n=== Television appearances ===\nOxman is the focus of an episode of Netflix docu-series [[Abstract: The Art of Design]] (season 2, episode 2).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/09/20/netflix-abstract-the-art-of-design-2-olafur-eliasson/|title=Neri Oxman and Olafur Eliasson feature in second series of Netflix design documentary|date=2019-09-20|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Mediated Matter ==\nThe Mediated Matter group uses computational design, digital fabrication, materials science and synthetic biology to explore design possibilities in small and large structures.<ref name=\"oxmanlab\">{{cite web|url=https://www.media.mit.edu/research/groups/mediated-matter  |title=Mediated Matter group website |publisher=MIT Media Lab |date= |accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"weforum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/01/towards-a-material-ecology/|title=What if our buildings were grown, not built?|author=Neri Oxman|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref>  This sometimes involved taking images of a biological sample, developing algorithms to produce similar structures, and developing new manufacturing processes to realize the results.\nProjects have included wearables inspired by current and future environments,<ref>[https://www.wired.com/2012/05/design-fiction-neri-oxman-imaginary-beings-mythologies-of-the-not-yet/ Design Fiction: Neri Oxman, \u201cImaginary Beings: Mythologies of the Not Yet\u201d], Wired magazine. May 12, 2012</ref>\nsolar-powered and biodegradable designs,<ref name=\"mushtari\">[http://www.archdaily.com/769818/neri-oxmans-mushtari-is-a-3d-printed-wearable-that-makes-products-from-sunlight \u201cMushtari\u201d Is a 3D Printed Wearable That Makes Products from Sunlight], ArchDaily. July 12, 2015</ref> new artistic techniques,\nand experimental surfaces, walls, coverings and load-bearing elements. Some of these involved combining work from many fields.\n\n=== Organic and natural fabrication ===\nA number of Oxman's works have involved fabrication by animals or by natural processes.\n\nThe ''Silk Pavilion'', an installation designed in 2013, was noted for its fabrication method as much as its final form.  It was woven by 6,500 free-ranging silkworms on a nylon-frame dome.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://www.materialecology.com/assets/pdf/Conf_FABRICATE_ArticleOxmanLaucks.pdf|title=Fabricate: Negotiating Design and Making|last=Oxman|first=Neri|last2=Laucks|first2=Jared|last3=Kayser|first3=Markus|display-authors=etal|publisher=gta Verlag|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=249\u2013255|chapter=Silk Pavilion: A case study in fibre-based digital fabrication}}</ref>  Experiments with the silkworms identified how they would respond to different surfaces, and what would encourage them to spin onto an existing structure rather than spinning a cocoon.  The frame of a large polyhedral dome was loosely woven by a robotic arm out of thin nylon threads, and suspended in an open room.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/thousands-of-silkworms-and-one-robot-made-this-intricat-511217252|title=Thousands of silkworms and one robot made this intricate sculpture|last=Dvorsky|first=George|work=io9|access-date=March 19, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>  The dome was designed with gaps where it would be warmest.  Silkworms were released onto the frame in waves, where they added layers of silk before being removed.  This involved engineering, [[sericulture]], and modelling sun in the room.  The resulting installation art was hung so that people could stand inside it.\n\nThe ''Ocean Pavilion,'' an installation from 2014, included a water-based fabrication platform where structures were built out of chitosan, a water-soluble organic fiber similar to chitin.  Structural pillars and long delicate leaves were made by varying how the fibers were deposited. The result was a combination of hard and soft structures, changing from solid to willowy over the length of a branch or leaf, but all made from the same base material.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ''Synthetic Apiary'', a room-sized installation built in 2015, studied the behavior of bees in an entirely indoor environment, including how they built hives in and around different structures.  This was developed in collaboration with a beekeeping company, as a way of testing possible responses to colony loss, and exploring how biological niches could be explicitly integrated into buildings.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.archdaily.com/796769/neri-oxman-plus-mediated-matter-create-synthetic-apiaries-to-combat-honeybee-colony-loss|title=Neri Oxman + Mediated Matter Create Synthetic Apiary to Combat Honeybee Colony Loss|date=October 5, 2016|newspaper=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 3D printing developments ===\nMediated Matter worked extensively with various 3D printing techniques, developing their own methods and collaborating with printing companies such as [[Stratasys]].  Projects have ranged in scale from enclosures and large furniture, to artwork and clothes, to biocomposites, artificial valves, and DNA assembly. The group designed a prototype printer with a robotic arm that could build 8-foot tall structures all around itself in outdoor spaces, and a quick-curing printer that makes free-standing objects without support structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://matter.media.mit.edu/publications/article/freeform-3d-printing-towards-a-sustainable-approach-to-additive-manufacturi|title=Freeform 3D Printing: Towards a Sustainable Approach to Additive Manufacturing|last=|first=|date=2013|website=|access-date=March 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302113304/http://matter.media.mit.edu/publications/article/freeform-3d-printing-towards-a-sustainable-approach-to-additive-manufacturi|archive-date=March 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Oxman printed her first set of body-sized wearables, a collection titled ''Imaginary Beings'' and inspired by legendary creatures.  This was followed by ''Anthozoa'', a dress developed in collaboration with fashion designer [[Iris van Herpen]] and materials engineer Craig Carter. These were some of the first examples of multi-color and multi-material 3D printing a human scale,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.3dprinter.net/the-not-so-secret-stratasys-objet-multi-color-3d-printer|title=The not-so-secret Objet multi-color 3D printer|last=|first=|date=May 7, 2012|work=3D Printer|access-date=February 28, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> using a bright palette with fine granular control of color and texture.  In 2015, she designed the ''Wanderers'' collection with Christoph Bader and Dominik Kolb, inspired by ideas of interplanetary exploration. That earned Fast Company's award for Design Innovation. The most influential of the Wanderers was the ''Living Mushtari'' chestpiece, a model digestive tract filled with liquid and a colony of photosynthetic [[Cyanobacteria|bacteria]] and ''[[E. coli]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/mit-professor-creates-3d-printed-wearable-skin-space-exploration-1477862|title=MIT professor creates 3D printed 'wearable skin' for space exploration|date=December 3, 2014|access-date=August 7, 2016}}</ref>  Producing ''Mushtari'' required new modeling methods for printing long flexible tubes with varying thickness.\n\nIn 2016, she produced ''Rottlace,'' a set of 3D-printed feathered, filamented, and textured masks.  These were made for the artist [[Bj\u00f6rk]],<ref>From \"Ro\u00f0laus\", Icelandic for \"skinless\".</ref> based on a 3D scan of her face. Bj\u00f6rk wore these in the world's first 360\u00b0 VR performance.<ref name=\"bjork\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dentsulab.tokyo/events/20160628/|title=Making of Bj\u00f6rk Digital|last=|first=|date=|access-date=February 28, 2017|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423212441/http://dentsulab.tokyo/events/20160628|archive-date=April 23, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  She also began designing ''Vespers'', a collection of 15 death masks. Described as \"like something out of ''Alien''\", each mask is a curved translucent shell the size of a face, within which a detailed pattern is printed in clouds of color and shadow. This tested the limits of how small voxels of color could be inside a 3D printed solid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/gallery/death-masks-neri-oxman-vesper|title=Haunting 3D-printed death masks are like something out of Alien|work=WIRED UK|access-date=March 10, 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"vespers\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/vespers-the-latest-mask-collection-by-mits-neri-oxman_o|title=Vespers, the Latest Mask Collection by MIT's Neri Oxman|date=December 15, 2016|work=Architect|access-date=March 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOxman has also premiered new printing tools and processes. In 2015, she designed ''Gemini'', a large chaise lounge combining a milled wood shell with a 3D-printed surface.  Both the outer shell and the texture of the inner surface were designed to produce a soothing acoustical environment for someone reclining in it. ''Gemini'' was later acquired by [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SF MoMA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3dprintingindustry.com/news/neri-oxman-pursues-3d-printing-multi-materials-latest-mythical-installation-gemini-25368/|title=Neri Oxman Further Pursues 3D Printing with Multi-Materials for her Latest Mythical Installation \u2014 \"GEMINI\"|access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Matter-glass-printer.webm|thumb|The ''G3DP'' glass printing process]]\nAlso in 2015, a Mediated Matter team developed ''G3DP'',<ref>{{Cite book|title=Additive Manufacturing of Optically Transparent Glass|last=Klein|first=John|publisher=Mediated Matter|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> the first 3D printer for optically transparent glass.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2015/3-d-printing-transparent-glass-0914|title=Printing transparent glass in 3-D|last=Chandler|first=David|date=September 14, 2015|work=MIT News|access-date=July 9, 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://singularityhub.com/2015/09/09/watch-mits-breakthrough-3d-printer-pour-molten-glass-like-honey/|title=Watch MIT's Breakthrough 3D Printer Pour Molten Glass Like Honey|last=Dorrier|first=Jason|date=September 9, 2015|website=Singularity Hub|publisher=Singularity University|access-date=August 1, 2016}}</ref> At the time, sintering 3D printers could print with glass powder, but the results were brittle and opaque.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.shapeways.com/blog/archives/401-you-can-now-3d-print-in-glass-with-shapeways.html|title=you can now 3D print in glass with Shapeways|last=joris|date=April 14, 2010|work=The Shapeways Blog|access-date=March 19, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> ''G3DP'' was designed in collaboration with MIT's Glass Lab and the [[Wyss Institute for Biologically Inspired Engineering|Wyss Institute]], emulating traditional glass working processes. Molten glass was poured in fine streams and cooled in an annealing chamber, yielding precision suitable for [[Glass art|art]] and consumer products, and glass strength suitable for [[Architectural glass|architectural]] elements.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://optics.org/news/6/9/3|title=US group develops 3D-printing technique for optical glass|last=Peach|first=Matthew|date=September 1, 2015|website=optics.org|publisher=SPIE|access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> The process allowed close control of color, transparency, thickness and texture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/mits-neri-oxman-on-the-true-beauty-of-3d-printed-glass_o|title=MIT's Neri Oxman on the True Beauty of 3D Printed Glass|date=August 28, 2015|access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> Changing the height and speed of the nozzle produced uniform loops, turning the printer into a \"molden glass sewing machine\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-35171408|title='Sewing' with molten glass and maths|last=Webb|first=Jonathan|date=January 1, 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=March 19, 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> A set of glass vessels made with this printer went on exhibit at the Cooper Hewitt and other museums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooperhewitt.org/events/current-exhibitions/beauty-cooper-hewitt-design-triennial/ |title=Cooper Hewitt Design Triennial, ''Beauty'' |date=July 2016|publisher=Cooper Hewitt}}</ref> and a 10-foot tall sculpture of light and printed glass, ''YET'', was designed for the 2017 Milan Design Week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.linformatique.org/exposition-lexus-yet-milan-design-week-neri-oxman.html|title=L'exposition \" Lexus Yet \" \u00e0 la Milan Design Week en collaboration avec Neri Oxman {{!}} Linformatique.org|last=Manon|first=Victoria|date=February 17, 2017|work=Linformatique.org|access-date=February 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217182418/http://www.linformatique.org/exposition-lexus-yet-milan-design-week-neri-oxman.html|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=dead|language=fr-FR}}</ref>\n\n== Publications and essays ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n* 2016: What if our buildings were grown, not built?<ref name=\"weforum\"/>\n* 2015: Material Ecology<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|last2=Ortiz|first2=Christine|last3=Gramazio|first3=Fabio|last4=Kohler|first4=Matthias|date=March 1, 2015|title=Material ecology|journal=Computer-Aided Design|series=Material Ecology|volume=60|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2014.05.009|hdl=1721.1/107168|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2014: Gemini: <small>Multi-Material Digital Design Fabrication</small><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|last2=Dikovsky|first2=Daniel|last3=Belocon|first3=Boris|last4=Carter|first4=W. Craig|date=September 1, 2014|title=Gemini: Engaging Experiential and Feature Scales Through Multimaterial Digital Design and Hybrid Additive\u2013Subtractive Fabrication|journal=3D Printing and Additive Manufacturing|volume=1|issue=3|pages=108\u2013114|doi=10.1089/3dp.2014.1505|issn=2329-7662|hdl=1721.1/108169|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2011: Variable Property Rapid Prototyping<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|date=March 1, 2011|title=Variable property rapid prototyping|journal=Virtual and Physical Prototyping|volume=6|issue=1|pages=3\u201331|doi=10.1080/17452759.2011.558588|issn=1745-2759}}</ref>\n* 2006: Tropisms: <small>Computing Theoretical Morphospaces of Branching Growth Systems</small><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oxman|first=Neri|date=2006|title=Collective Intelligence in Design, pg 20.|url=|journal=AD (Architectural Design)|volume=76|issue=5|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|right}}\n'''Group publications'''\n* 2016: 3D Printed Multimaterial Microfluidic Valve<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keating|first=Steven J.|last2=Gariboldi|first2=Maria Isabella|last3=Patrick|first3=William G.|last4=Sharma|first4=Sunanda|last5=Kong|first5=David S.|last6=Oxman|first6=Neri|date=August 15, 2016|title=3D Printed Multimaterial Microfluidic Valve|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=11|issue=8|pages=e0160624|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0160624|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4985141|pmid=27525809|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1160624K}}</ref>\n* 2016: DNA Assembly in 3D Printed Fluidics<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patrick|first=William G.|last2=Nielsen|first2=Alec A. K.|last3=Keating|first3=Steven J.|last4=Levy|first4=Taylor J.|last5=Wang|first5=Che-Wei|last6=Rivera|first6=Jaime J.|last7=Mondrag\u00f3n-Palomino|first7=Octavio|last8=Carr|first8=Peter A.|last9=Voigt|first9=Christopher A.; Oxman, Neri; Kong, David S.|date=December 30, 2015|title=DNA Assembly in 3D Printed Fluidics|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0143636|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0143636|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4699221|pmid=26716448|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1043636P}}</ref>\n* 2015: Flow-based Fabrication<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Duro-Royo|first=Jorge|last2=Mogas-Soldevila|first2=Laia|last3=Oxman|first3=Neri|date=December 1, 2015|title=Flow-based fabrication: An integrated computational workflow for design and digital additive manufacturing of multifunctional heterogeneously structured objects|journal=Computer-Aided Design|volume=69|pages=143\u2013154|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2015.05.005|hdl=1721.1/112152|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2015: Additive Manufacturing of Optically Transparent Glass<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=John|last2=Stern|first2=Michael|last3=Franchin|first3=Giorgia|last4=Kayser|first4=Markus|last5=Inamura|first5=Chikara|last6=Dave|first6=Shreya|last7=Weaver|first7=James C.|last8=Houk|first8=Peter|last9=Colombo|first9=Paolo; Yang, Maria; Oxman, Neri|date=August 19, 2015|title=Additive Manufacturing of Optically Transparent Glass|journal=3D Printing and Additive Manufacturing|volume=2|issue=3|pages=92\u2013105|doi=10.1089/3dp.2015.0021|issn=2329-7662|pmid=|hdl=1721.1/101831|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Exhibited works==\nOxman's early projects took the form of example surfaces, furniture, or objects that could be worn or put on display.  Most were exhibited in museums.  More recent work included temporary and interactive installations.  Some, such as the ''Ocean Pavilion'' and ''G3DP,'' included a production process;<ref name=\":2\" /> others, such as the ''Silk Pavilion'' and ''Synthetic Apiary,'' included biological observation and research on the exhibit.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Selected works ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''Cartesian Wax'',  ''Monocoque'',  ''Subterrain''<ref>''Variable Property Analysis and Fabrication of a Butterfly Wing''</ref> (2007, [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://neri.media.mit.edu/projects|title=Project list|last=|first=|date=|website=Personal site|publisher=MIT Media Lab|access-date=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Raycounting'', ''Penumbra'' (2007, MoMA)\n* ''Fibonacci\u2019s Mashrabiya'' (2009, 12, [[Centre Georges Pompidou|Centre Pompidou]])\n* ''Beast: <small>Prototype for a Chaise Longue</small>'' (2010, MoS)\n* ''Carpal Skin''<ref>''Prototype for a Carpal Tunnel Syndrome Splint''</ref> (2010, [[Museum of Science (Boston)|Museum of Science]])\n* ''Silk Pavilion'' (2012), installation \n* ''<u>Imaginary Beings</u>'' (2012, Centre Pompidou)\n** 18 'wearables for demigods': ''Gravida'', ''Pneuma'', ''Remora''\n{{clear|right}}\n[[File:G3DP glass bowl-sm.png|thumb|upright=0.4|right|''G3DP'' bowl]]\n* ''Ocean Pavilion'' (2013), installation\n* ''Anthozoa'' (2013, [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|MFA]]), couture dress\n* ''Gemini'' (2015, [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SF MoMA]]), acoustical chaise\n* ''<u>Wanderers</u>'' collection (2015):<ref>[https://3dprint.com/26925/wearable-skins-triple-jetting/ Wearable skins], Sarah Anderson Goehrke. 3DPrint.com, November 25, 2014.</ref>\n** ''Otaared'', ''Qamar'', ''Zuhai''\n** ''Living Mushtari''\n* ''G3DP'' (2015), 3D printer & glasswork\n* ''Synthetic Apiary'' (2015), installation<ref>[http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/synthetic-apiary Synthetic apiary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817093154/http://matter.media.mit.edu/environments/details/synthetic-apiary |date=August 17, 2018 }}: a perpetual spring environment.  Retrieved September 15, 2016</ref>\n* ''Rottlace'' (2016, Bj\u00f6rk), masks<ref name=\"bjork\"/>\n* ''Vespers'' (2016\u20132018), death mask series<ref name=\"vespers\"/>\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Gallery ===\n\n; Art, surfaces, and furniture\n<gallery>\nFile:Neri Oxman CartesianWax 03.tif|''Cartesian Wax'' surface\nFile:Monocoque-2010-moma.jpg|''Monocoque 2'', [[MoMA]]\nFile:Oxman Raycounting-10 MoMA.tiff|''Raycounting'', multiply lit\nFile:Pneuma 2 by Neri Oxman at the 3D, printing the future exhibition at the Science Museum, London.JPG|''Pneuma 2''\nFile:Caustic patterns of a 3D printed glass structure.jpg|''G3DP'' printed glasswork\n</gallery>\n\n; Wearables, machines, and installations\n<gallery>\nFile:NeriOxman-VanHerpenShow.jpg|''Anthozoa'' dress\nFile:Matter-glass-printer.webm|''G3DP'' printing process\nFile:GLASS_II_-_Mediated_Matter.webm|2d gen G3DP\nFile:Matter-silk-pavilion.webm|Silk Pavilion process\nFile:Synthetic-apiary.webm|Synthetic Apiary studies\nFile:Mushtari.webm|''Mushtari'' living corset\nFile:Oxman-wanderers-morphology.jpg|Family of morphologies used for ''Wanderers''\nFile:Vespers_Series_III_-_Mediated_Matter.webm|Vespers death masks\n</gallery>\n\n=== Selected exhibits ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Beijing International Art Biennale|Beijing Art Biennale]]: 2006\u20132010\n*[[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]], New York: 2007, 2010 (<small>''Action: Design over Time''</small>), 2015 (<small>''This Is for Everyone''</small>)\n*[[Museum of Science (Boston)|Museum of Science]], Boston: 2012 (<small>''Neri Oxman:'' ''At the Frontier of Ecological Design''</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mos.org/sites/dev-elvis.mos.org/files/docs/advancement/mos_magazine_fall-2009.pdf|title=Neri Oxman: At the Frontier of Ecological Design|last=|first=|date=Fall 2009|website=|publisher=Museum of Science, Boston|access-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref>)\n*[[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|Cooper Hewitt Museum]]: 2015 (<small>''Making Design''</small>), 2016 (<small>''Beauty''</small>)\n*[[Centre Georges Pompidou|Centre Pompidou]], Paris: 2012  (<small>''Imaginary Beings'' exhibit, ''Multiversit\u00e9s Cr\u00e9atives''</small><ref>[https://www.wired.com/2012/05/design-fiction-neri-oxman-imaginary-beings-mythologies-of-the-not-yet/ Imaginary Beings: Mythologies of the Not Yet], ''Wired'', May 2012.</ref>)\n*[[Science Museum, London]]: 2012 & 2013 (<small>''3D PRINT SHOW''</small><ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2013/mar/10/entertainment/la-et-cm-3d-print-show-20130310 3-D printing produces a fresh creative outlet for artists],  L.J. Williamson, LA Times. March 10, 2013.</ref>)\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|Museum of Fine Arts]], Boston: 2013, 2016 (<small>''#techstyle: Production''</small><ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/2016/03/07/what-future-fashion-mfa-techstyle-show-looks-for-answers/s5lyjSDP4V89aG9cQpEhVM/story.html What is the future of fashion?], Joe Incollingo, Boston Globe. March 7, 2016.</ref>)\n*[[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|Museum of Applied Arts]], Vienna: 2014 (<small>''150 Years of the MAK''</small><ref>[http://blog.mak.at/remora-exemplary-150-years-of-the-mak-from-arts-and-crafts-to-design/ Remora \u2013 EXEMPLARY: 150 YEARS OF THE MAK], MAK Blog. July 8, 2014.</ref>)\n*[[National Gallery of Victoria]], Victoria: 2017 (<small>''NGV Triennial''</small><ref>[http://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/the+ngv+announces+its+biggest+installation+of+the+year,42127 The NGV announces its biggest installation of the year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003142324/http://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/the+ngv+announces+its+biggest+installation+of+the+year,42127 |date=October 3, 2017 }}, Angelica Xidias. ''[[Vogue Magazine]]'', March 8, 2017.</ref>)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nOxman is a senior fellow in the [[Design Futures Council]], and won the [[The Vilcek Foundation|Vilcek Prize]] in Design in 2014.<ref name=\"vilcek\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.mit.edu/2014/media-labs-neri-oxman-awarded-vilcek-prize-|title=Media Lab's Neri Oxman awarded Vilcek Prize|website=MIT News|accessdate=November 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she was on ICON\u2019s list of the \u201c20 Most Influential Architects to Shape Our Future.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Architect, Designer Neri Oxman Uses Principles of Nature to Create, Build|last=|first=|date=November 3, 2010|work=|publisher=Targeted News Service|access-date=|via=}}</ref>  In 2012, ''Shalom Life'' ranked her number 1 on its list of \u201cmost talented, intelligent, funny, and gorgeous Jewish women in the world.\"<ref name=\"Ashley Baylen\"/><ref name=\"esquire.com\"/>\n\nOther awards include:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[London Design Festival]] Design Innovation medal (2018)[https://www.londondesignfestival.com/design-innovation-medal-neri-oxman]\n* MIT [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology Police Department|Collier Medal]] (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrweb.mit.edu/rewards/recipient/award-recipients/2016/collier-medal/neri-oxman|title=2016 Collier Medal {{!}} Neri Oxman|last=|first=|date=|website=hrweb.mit.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-23}}</ref> \n* Cultural Leader, [[World Economic Forum]] (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://widgets.weforum.org/davos-arts/2016/|title=Arts and Culture at Davos 2016|website=widgets.weforum.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-23}}</ref> \n* Innovation by Design Award, [[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] (2015), for ''Wanderers''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/773938/neri-oxman-and-som-among-fast-companys-innovation-by-design-award-winners|title=Neri Oxman and SOM Among Fast Company's Innovation By Design Award Winners|date=September 18, 2015|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[American Institute of Architects]] Women in Design (2014)<ref>[http://abexpo.com/conference/women-in-design-symposium-the-value-of-design/women-in-design-2014-award-winners AIA Women in Design award winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815181830/http://abexpo.com/conference/women-in-design-symposium-the-value-of-design/women-in-design-2014-award-winners |date=August 15, 2016 }}, 2014</ref>\n* [[Carnegie Corporation|Carnegie]] \"Pride of America\" Award (2014)<ref>[http://greatimmigrants.carnegie.org/profile/neri-oxman/ Pride of America Honorees] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815203354/http://greatimmigrants.carnegie.org/profile/neri-oxman/ |date=August 15, 2016 }} page</ref>\n* [[Vilcek Foundation|Vilcek Prize]] in Design (2014)<ref name=\"vilcek\"/>\n* Senior Fellow, [[Design Futures Council]] (2013)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://designfuturescouncil.com/about/fellows/|title=Senior Fellows - Design Futures Council|work=Design Futures Council|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324174034/http://designfuturescouncil.com/about/fellows/|archivedate=March 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Earth Award for Future Crucial Design]] (2009)<ref>[http://bustler.net/news/684/fab-recology-designer-neri-oxman-named-winner-of-first-earth-award Neri Oxman named winner of first Earth Award], Bustler, January 13, 2009.</ref>\n* Carter Manny Citation, [[Graham Foundation for Advanced Studies in the Fine Arts|Graham Foundation for the Arts]] (2008)\n* [[LafargeHolcim Foundation for Sustainable Construction|Holcim Foundation]] Next Generation Award (2008), for \"microstructure research for building skins\"<ref>[https://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/Article/top-sustainable-construction-projects-in-north-america-honored \"Top sustainable construction projects in North America honored\"], Holcim Foundation</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://matter.media.mit.edu Official site]\n\n{{Portal bar|Architecture}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oxman, Neri}}\n[[Category:Israeli architects]]\n[[Category:Israeli designers]]\n[[Category:Israeli expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hebrew Reali School alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:People from Haifa]]\n[[Category:MIT Media Lab people]]\n", "name_user": "Celineshaw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Impact as a role model", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neri_Oxman"}
